{"title_page": "TVU Networks", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| type = [[Private company|Private]]\n| foundation = 2005\n| logo = TVUnetworks Logo.svg\n| name = TVU Networks Corporation\n| location = [[Mountain View, California|Mountain View]], [[California]], United States\n| key_people = Paul Shen, [[Chief Executive Officer]]\n| industry = [[Technology]]\n| products = TVU Alert, TVU Anywhere, TVU AP ENPS Integration, TVU Aerial Newsgathering Pack, TVU Booking Service, TVU Command Center, TVU Era, TVU Grid, TVU ''Me'', TVU MediaMind, TVU MLink, TVU One, TVU One TM1000G, TVU Producer, TVU Router, TVU Remote Production System, TVU Timelock, TVU Transcriber\n| homepage = {{URL |www.tvunetworks.com}}\n}}\n\n'''TVU Networks Corporation''' is a technology company that provides IP-based live video solutions. The company, which was founded in 2005, is headquartered in [[Mountain View, California]] and also has offices in [[Raleigh, North Carolina]], [[Shanghai]] and [[Beijing]], China, [[Uttar Pradesh]], India and [[Barcelona]], Spain.\n\n==Company==\n\nTVU Networks offers IP-based solutions for live broadcast. Its solutions are deployed across a variety of industries including news broadcast, web streaming, law enforcement, sports and government. TVU Networks\u2019 products have been used to cover a number of events around the world including the Royal Wedding, the World Cup, the London Summer Olympics and Sochi Winter Olympics, and U.S. presidential elections.\n\n==History==\n\nThe original flagship product of TVU Networks was TVUPlayer. TVUPlayer was [[freeware]] [[IPTV]] software application for [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] and [[macOS|Mac OS X]] to watch several dozen TV channels over the Internet. TVU did not broadcast these channels, but provided a platform for broadcasters to distribute content online. It was the responsibility of the individual who broadcasts a particular channel on TVU to keep the channel running and ensure that the content can be legally transmitted. It was unknown to the viewer who the broadcaster was. Broadcasts originated from either a large broadcasting company itself, which chose to provide viewers with its broadcast, or individual broadcasters who created their own content or captured public broadcasts and rebroadcast them on TVU.\n\nIt was debated whether TVU Networks operated an illegal service by  knowingly providing users with an opportunity to watch copyrighted content without the permission of content owners. However, the company did not provide the illegal content itself due the fact that was the responsibility of the user who provided the content to verify its legality.<ref name=\"cnet1\">{{Cite news |url= http://news.cnet.com/TVU+Networks+exec+grapples+with+copyright+questions/2100-1026_3-6132672.html |title= TVU chief grapples with copyright questions |work= CNET News |accessdate= November 27, 2013 |author= Greg Sandoval |date= November 6, 2006 |archiveurl= https://archive.today/20130119174026/http://news.cnet.com/TVU-Networks-exec-grapples-with-copyright-questions/2100-1026_3-6132672.html |archivedate= January 19, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=  }}</ref>\n\nTVU Networks shut down service to the TVUPlayer on February 25, 2013.<ref>{{Cite web |title= TVU Networks shut down service to the TVU Player on February 25, 2013. |work= Company web site |url= http://www.tvunetworks.com/faq.html |accessdate= November 27, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131203015357/http://www.tvunetworks.com/faq.html |archivedate= December 3, 2013 |df=  }}</ref>\n\n==Products==\n\n===TVU Alert===\n\nTVU Alert is a cloud-based service that allows users to instantly notify their entire organization or part of their organization about important information.\n\n===TVU Anywhere===\n\nTVU Anywhere is an app that turns mobile devices or laptops into transmitters that use aggregated cellular and WiFi connections to stream high-quality video.\n\n===TVU AP ENPS Integration===\n\nTVU AP ENPS Integration is a collaboration between TVU Networks and the Associated Press to create a newsroom workflow geared toward streamlining the newsgathering process from shooting to editing.\n\n===TVU Aerial Newsgathering Pack===\nThe TVU Aerial Newsgathering Pack integrates its TVU One mobile transmitter with drone technology to enable live high-definition transmission from in the air.\n\n===TVU Booking Service===\nTVU Booking Service lets stations plan and manage streams. Booking Service automatically takes streams live according to a set schedule, and switches between streams without the need for an operator.\n\n===TVU Command Center===\nTVU Command Center is a cloud-based management system that grants full control over all TVU products and services. Through Command Center, users can adjust latency and bit-rate on TVU transmitters, track receiver locations through a map, add and remove supported devices and manage all TVU Grid content.\n\n===TVU Era===\nTVU Era is a cost-friendly version of the TVU One mobile transmitter and other professional video encoders similar to it. It has most of the features of the TVU One but is designed to be used with a single IP Ethernet connection.\n\n===TVU G-Link===\nTVU G-Link is a point-to-point transmission solution that allows video to be sent from one location to another using a public Internet connection.\n\n===TVU G-Link 4K===\nTVU G-Link is a rack-mount contribution encoder that supports true 4K60P UHD HDR.\n\n===TVU Grid===\nTVU Grid is a live video switching, routing and distribution solution. It allows stations to distribute live streams to a scalable number of other Grid-enabled stations or locations via a web interface.\n\n===TVU ''Me''===\nTVU Me is a virtual marketplace where freelancers and independent production crews can make their live or recorded content available for exchange or purchase. They can also offer services for booking.\n\n===TVU MediaMind===\nTVU MediaMind is a story-centric workflow solution for acquiring, indexing, producing and distributing live video via the cloud. It uses Artificial Intelligence and automation to streamline the production process and archive media assets for reuse.\n\n===TVU MLink===\nTVU MLink is a transmitter designed for fixed use in vehicles or studios. It has the same functions as the TVU One but comes in a rack-mountable form, and is capable of integrating with satellite and microwave in addition to or in place of cellular or WiFi connections.\n\n===TVU One===\nTVU One is a compact mobile IP video transmitter that aggregates multiple connections to decode high quality video with 0.5-second latency. It can hold up to six embedded modems, with optional support for CAT12 3G/4G/LTE global modems. TVU One uses H.265/HEVC compression and runs on TVU Networks\u2019 patented transmission technology, Inverse StatMux Plus, or IS+.\nmm.m.., ?<<., mjkbkbk,n./\n\n===TVU One 4K===\n\nTVU One 4K is a version of the TVU One that supports 4K60P output. It is the first portable cellular backpack solution to transmit at this resolution.\n\n===TVU Producer===\nTVU Producer is a cloud-based production solution that allows multi-channel IP video switching with titling and graphics capabilities. Users can edit video on a web interface and simultaneously output it to social media or a CDN platform.\n\n===TVU Router===\nTVU Router is a portable Internet access point that uses the patented Inverse StatMux Plus to aggregate communication links to provide up to 200Mb/s of secure, stable, high-bandwidth IP connection.\n\n===TVU Remote Production System===\nTVU Remote Production System (also known as TVU RPS) uses existing studio infrastructure and a standard Internet connection for remote live multi-camera production with up to six synchronized transmissions. It is part of TVU\u2019s Remote Production solutions.\n\n===TVU Talkshow(TM)===\nTVU Talkshow(TM) is a cost-effective turnkey solution for live show and event production with optional bi-directional viewer participation.\n\n===TVU Timelock===\nTVU Timelock is another part of TVU\u2019s Remote Production solutions. It sets up to six TVU transmitters at the same latency to transmit to a video switcher for remote multi-camera production.\n\n===TVU Transcriber===\nTVU Transcriber converts speech to text in real time for both live and recorded videos. It supports multiple languages, can identify and mute profanity, and can output audio as text in a file format to be used for auditing.\n\n==Awards==\n===2019===\nBroadcast Production Awards, Newscast Studio for TVU CAS<br />NAB Show Product of the Year Awards, AI/Machine Learning for TVU MediaMind Appliance<br />NewBay Best of Show Award from TV Technology for TVU One 4K\n\n===2018===\nNewBay Best of Show Award from TV Technology for TVU Nano with Router<br />TV Technology Product Innovation Award for TVU MediaMind<br />Digital Video Product Innovation Award for TVU Producer\n\n===2017===\nNewBay Best of Show Award from TV Technology for TVU One with support for H.265/HEVC video compression standard<br />NewBay Best of Show Award from Video Edge for TVU Producer<br />NewBay Product Innovation Award from TV Technology for TVU Timelock<br />NewBay Industry Innovator Award from TV Technology for Paul Shen, TVU Networks CEO<br />Best of Show Award from TVBEurope for TVU Router<br />Streaming Media Magazine\u2019s 2017 Streaming Media 100\n\n===2016===\nNewBay Best of Show Award from TV Technology for TVU Remote Production System\n\n===2015===\nNewBay Best of Show Award from TV Technology for TVUPack TM8200 with Integrated MIMO Microwave Mesh technology\n\n===2014===\nNewBay Best of Show Award from TV Technology for TVUPack with Vislink Hybrid technology<br />NewBay Best of Show Award from TVBEurope for TVUPack with Vislink Hybrid technology<br />NewBay Best of Show Award from TV Technology for TVUPack\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060112042232/http://tvunetworks.com/ TVU Networks]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tvu Networks}}\n[[Category:Television technology]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Mountain View, California]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 2005]]\n[[Category:2005 establishments in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| type = [[Private company|Private]]\n| foundation = 2005\n| logo = TVUnetworks Logo.svg\n| name = TVU Networks Corporation\n| location = [[Mountain View, California|Mountain View]], [[California]], United States\n| key_people = Paul Shen, [[Chief Executive Officer]]\n| industry = [[Technology]]\n| products = TVU Alert, TVU Anywhere, TVU AP ENPS Integration, TVU Aerial Newsgathering Pack, TVU Booking Service, TVU Command Center, TVU Era, TVU Grid, TVU ''Me'', TVU MediaMind, TVU MLink, TVU One, TVU One TM1000G, TVU Producer, TVU Router, TVU Remote Production System, TVU Timelock, TVU Transcriber\n| homepage = {{URL |www.tvunetworks.com}}\n}}\n\n'''TVU Networks Corporation''' is a technology company that provides IP-based live video solutions. The company, which was founded in 2005, is headquartered in [[Mountain View, California]] and also has offices in [[Raleigh, North Carolina]], [[Shanghai]] and [[Beijing]], China, [[Uttar Pradesh]], India and [[Barcelona]], Spain.\n\n==Company==\n\nTVU Networks offers IP-based solutions for live broadcast. Its solutions are deployed across a variety of industries including news broadcast, web streaming, law enforcement, sports and government. TVU Networks\u2019 products have been used to cover a number of events around the world including the Royal Wedding, the World Cup, the London Summer Olympics and Sochi Winter Olympics, and U.S. presidential elections.\n\n==History==\n\nThe original flagship product of TVU Networks was TVUPlayer. TVUPlayer was [[freeware]] [[IPTV]] software application for [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] and [[macOS|Mac OS X]] to watch several dozen TV channels over the Internet. TVU did not broadcast these channels, but provided a platform for broadcasters to distribute content online. It was the responsibility of the individual who broadcasts a particular channel on TVU to keep the channel running and ensure that the content can be legally transmitted. It was unknown to the viewer who the broadcaster was. Broadcasts originated from either a large broadcasting company itself, which chose to provide viewers with its broadcast, or individual broadcasters who created their own content or captured public broadcasts and rebroadcast them on TVU.\n\nIt was debated whether TVU Networks operated an illegal service by  knowingly providing users with an opportunity to watch copyrighted content without the permission of content owners. However, the company did not provide the illegal content itself due the fact that was the responsibility of the user who provided the content to verify its legality.<ref name=\"cnet1\">{{Cite news |url= http://news.cnet.com/TVU+Networks+exec+grapples+with+copyright+questions/2100-1026_3-6132672.html |title= TVU chief grapples with copyright questions |work= CNET News |accessdate= November 27, 2013 |author= Greg Sandoval |date= November 6, 2006 |archiveurl= https://archive.today/20130119174026/http://news.cnet.com/TVU-Networks-exec-grapples-with-copyright-questions/2100-1026_3-6132672.html |archivedate= January 19, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=  }}</ref>\n\nTVU Networks shut down service to the TVUPlayer on February 25, 2013.<ref>{{Cite web |title= TVU Networks shut down service to the TVU Player on February 25, 2013. |work= Company web site |url= http://www.tvunetworks.com/faq.html |accessdate= November 27, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131203015357/http://www.tvunetworks.com/faq.html |archivedate= December 3, 2013 |df=  }}</ref>\n\n==Products==\n\n===TVU Alert===\n\nTVU Alert is a cloud-based service that allows users to instantly notify their entire organization or part of their organization about important information.\n\n===TVU Anywhere===\n\nTVU Anywhere is an app that turns mobile devices or laptops into transmitters that use aggregated cellular and WiFi connections to stream high-quality video.\n\n===TVU AP ENPS Integration===\n\nTVU AP ENPS Integration is a collaboration between TVU Networks and the Associated Press to create a newsroom workflow geared toward streamlining the newsgathering process from shooting to editing.\n\n===TVU Aerial Newsgathering Pack===\nThe TVU Aerial Newsgathering Pack integrates its TVU One mobile transmitter with drone technology to enable live high-definition transmission from in the air.\n\n===TVU Booking Service===\nTVU Booking Service lets stations plan and manage streams. Booking Service automatically takes streams live according to a set schedule, and switches between streams without the need for an operator.\n\n===TVU Command Center===\nTVU Command Center is a cloud-based management system that grants full control over all TVU products and services. Through Command Center, users can adjust latency and bit-rate on TVU transmitters, track receiver locations through a map, add and remove supported devices and manage all TVU Grid content.\n\n===TVU Era===\nTVU Era is a cost-friendly version of the TVU One mobile transmitter and other professional video encoders similar to it. It has most of the features of the TVU One but is designed to be used with a single IP Ethernet connection.\n\n===TVU G-Link===\nTVU G-Link is a point-to-point transmission solution that allows video to be sent from one location to another using a public Internet connection.\n\n===TVU G-Link 4K===\nTVU G-Link is a rack-mount contribution encoder that supports true 4K60P UHD HDR.\n\n===TVU Grid===\nTVU Grid is a live video switching, routing and distribution solution. It allows stations to distribute live streams to a scalable number of other Grid-enabled stations or locations via a web interface.\n\n===TVU ''Me''===\nTVU Me is a virtual marketplace where freelancers and independent production crews can make their live or recorded content available for exchange or purchase. They can also offer services for booking.\n\n===TVU MediaMind===\nTVU MediaMind is a story-centric workflow solution for acquiring, indexing, producing and distributing live video via the cloud. It uses Artificial Intelligence and automation to streamline the production process and archive media assets for reuse.\n\n===TVU MLink===\nTVU MLink is a transmitter designed for fixed use in vehicles or studios. It has the same functions as the TVU One but comes in a rack-mountable form, and is capable of integrating with satellite and microwave in addition to or in place of cellular or WiFi connections.\n\n===TVU One===\nTVU One is a compact mobile IP video transmitter that aggregates multiple connections to decode high quality video with 0.5-second latency. It can hold up to six embedded modems, with optional support for CAT12 3G/4G/LTE global modems. TVU One uses H.265/HEVC compression and runs on TVU Networks\u2019 patented transmission technology, Inverse StatMux Plus, or IS+.\n\n===TVU One 4K===\n\nTVU One 4K is a version of the TVU One that supports 4K60P output. It is the first portable cellular backpack solution to transmit at this resolution.\n\n===TVU Producer===\nTVU Producer is a cloud-based production solution that allows multi-channel IP video switching with titling and graphics capabilities. Users can edit video on a web interface and simultaneously output it to social media or a CDN platform.\n\n===TVU Router===\nTVU Router is a portable Internet access point that uses the patented Inverse StatMux Plus to aggregate communication links to provide up to 200Mb/s of secure, stable, high-bandwidth IP connection.\n\n===TVU Remote Production System===\nTVU Remote Production System (also known as TVU RPS) uses existing studio infrastructure and a standard Internet connection for remote live multi-camera production with up to six synchronized transmissions. It is part of TVU\u2019s Remote Production solutions.\n\n===TVU Talkshow(TM)===\nTVU Talkshow(TM) is a cost-effective turnkey solution for live show and event production with optional bi-directional viewer participation.\n\n===TVU Timelock===\nTVU Timelock is another part of TVU\u2019s Remote Production solutions. It sets up to six TVU transmitters at the same latency to transmit to a video switcher for remote multi-camera production.\n\n===TVU Transcriber===\nTVU Transcriber converts speech to text in real time for both live and recorded videos. It supports multiple languages, can identify and mute profanity, and can output audio as text in a file format to be used for auditing.\n\n==Awards==\n===2019===\nBroadcast Production Awards, Newscast Studio for TVU CAS<br />NAB Show Product of the Year Awards, AI/Machine Learning for TVU MediaMind Appliance<br />NewBay Best of Show Award from TV Technology for TVU One 4K\n\n===2018===\nNewBay Best of Show Award from TV Technology for TVU Nano with Router<br />TV Technology Product Innovation Award for TVU MediaMind<br />Digital Video Product Innovation Award for TVU Producer\n\n===2017===\nNewBay Best of Show Award from TV Technology for TVU One with support for H.265/HEVC video compression standard<br />NewBay Best of Show Award from Video Edge for TVU Producer<br />NewBay Product Innovation Award from TV Technology for TVU Timelock<br />NewBay Industry Innovator Award from TV Technology for Paul Shen, TVU Networks CEO<br />Best of Show Award from TVBEurope for TVU Router<br />Streaming Media Magazine\u2019s 2017 Streaming Media 100\n\n===2016===\nNewBay Best of Show Award from TV Technology for TVU Remote Production System\n\n===2015===\nNewBay Best of Show Award from TV Technology for TVUPack TM8200 with Integrated MIMO Microwave Mesh technology\n\n===2014===\nNewBay Best of Show Award from TV Technology for TVUPack with Vislink Hybrid technology<br />NewBay Best of Show Award from TVBEurope for TVUPack with Vislink Hybrid technology<br />NewBay Best of Show Award from TV Technology for TVUPack\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060112042232/http://tvunetworks.com/ TVU Networks]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tvu Networks}}\n[[Category:Television technology]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Mountain View, California]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 2005]]\n[[Category:2005 establishments in California]]\n", "name_user": "202.59.136.126", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eTVU One)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TVU_Networks"}
{"title_page": "Jimmy Spencer (American football)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|name        = Jimmy Spencer\n|image       = <!-- Only free-content images are allowed for depicting living people -- see [[WP:NONFREE]]. -->\n|image_size  =\n|alt         =\n|caption     =\n|number      = 37, 22, 33\n|position    = [[Cornerback]]\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1969|3|29|mf=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Manning, South Carolina]]\n|death_date  =\n|death_place =\n|height_ft    = 5\n|height_in    = 9\n|weight_lbs   = 188\n|high_school  = [[Glades Central High School|Glades Central]]<br>([[Belle Glade, Florida]])\n|college     = [[Florida Gators football|Florida]]\n|draftyear   = 1991\n|draftround  = 8\n|draftpick   = 215\n|pastteams   = \n* [[Washington Redskins]] ({{NFL Year|1991}})*\n* [[New Orleans Saints]] ({{NFL Year|1992}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1995}})\n* [[Cincinnati Bengals]] ({{NFL Year|1996}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1997}})\n* [[San Diego Chargers]] ({{NFL Year|1998}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1999}})\n* [[Denver Broncos]] ({{NFL Year|2000}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2003}})\n|pastteamsnote = yes\n|highlights  = \n|statleague  = NFL\n|statlabel1  = Games played\n|statvalue1  = 177\n|statlabel2  = Games started\n|statvalue2  = 81\n|statlabel3  = [[Tackle (football move)|Tackles]]\n|statvalue3  = 418\n|statlabel4  = [[Interception]]s\n|statvalue4  = 26\n|statlabel5  = [[Fumble]]s recovered\n|statvalue5  = 8\n|nfl         = SPE526203\n| Spencer James and Olivia baker are going to get together in season 3.\n\n== Early years ==\n\nSpencer was born in [[Manning, South Carolina]].<ref name=pfrprofile>Pro-Football-Reference.com, Players, [https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/S/SpenJi21.htm  Jimmy Spencer].  Retrieved October 11, 2010.</ref>  He attended [[Glades Central High School]] in [[Belle Glade, Florida]],<ref name=dbfprofile>databaseFootball.com, Players, [http://www.databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=SPENCJIM02  Jimmy Spencer] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100214053827/http://databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=SPENCJIM02 |date=February 14, 2010 }}.  Retrieved October 11, 2010.</ref> and he played high school football for the Glades Central Raiders.\n\n== College career ==\n\nSpencer accepted an athletic scholarship to attend the [[University of Florida]] in Gainesville, Florida, where he played for coach [[Galen Hall]] and coach [[Steve Spurrier]]'s [[Florida Gators football]] teams from [[1988 Florida Gators football team|1988]] to [[1990 Florida Gators football team|1990]].<ref name=ufmediaguide>''[http://web.gatorzone.com/football/media/2011/media_guide.pdf  2011 Florida Gators Football Media Guide] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402035222/http://web.gatorzone.com/football/media/2011/media_guide.pdf |date=April 2, 2012 }}'', University Athletic Association, Gainesville, Florida, pp. 105, 110, 115, 185 (2011).  Retrieved August 31, 2011.</ref>  In 1990, he blocked a punt late in the fourth quarter, which [[Richard Fain]] recovered and returned twenty-five yards for a touchdown and providing the margin of victory in the Gators' 17\u201313 victory over the [[1992 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama Crimson Tide]] in Tuscaloosa, Alabama.<ref>Norm Carlson, ''University of Florida Football Vault: The History of the Florida Gators'', Whitman Publishing, LLC, Atlanta, Georgia, p. 107 (2007).</ref>  Spencer decided to forgo his final year of NCAA eligibility after his junior season in 1990, and made himself eligible for the [[NFL Draft]].\n\n== Professional career ==\n\nThe [[Washington Redskins]] selected Spencer in the eighth round (215th pick overall) of the [[1991 NFL Draft]].<ref>Pro Football Hall of Fame, Draft History, [http://www.profootballhof.com/history/story.aspx?story_id=2027  1991 National Football League Draft].  Retrieved October 11, 2010.</ref>  Spencer played for the New Orleans Saints from {{NFL Year|1992}} to {{NFL Year|1995}}, the Cincinnati Bengals in {{NFL Year|1996}} and {{NFL Year|1997}}, the San Diego Chargers in {{NFL Year|1998}} and {{NFL Year|1999}}, and the Denver Broncos from {{NFL Year|2000}} to {{NFL Year|2003}}.<ref name=nflprofile>National Football League, Historical Players, [http://www.nfl.com/players/jimmyspencer/profile?id=SPE526203  Jimmy Spencer].  Retrieved October 11, 2010.</ref>  Statistically, his best seasons were {{NFL Year|1994}}, 1995 and 1996, when he was a regular starter for New Orleans and then Cincinnati.<ref name=pfrprofile/>\n\nIn his twelve NFL seasons, Spencer played in 177 regular season games, and started eighty-one of them.<ref name=pfrprofile/>  He finished his NFL career with twenty-six [[interception]]s, two touchdown returns, eight fumble recoveries and one fumble recovery for a touchdown.<ref name=pfrprofile/>\n\nIn 2003, Spencer worked as an assistant defensive back coach with the Broncos in addition to playing, making him the first simultaneous player/coach in the NFL since Dan Reeves in 1972.\n\n== See also ==\n\n{{Portal|American football|Biography|College football}}\n* [[Florida Gators football, 1980\u201389]]\n* [[Florida Gators football, 1990\u201399]]\n* [[History of the Denver Broncos]]\n* [[List of Florida Gators football players in the NFL]]\n* [[List of New Orleans Saints players]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* Carlson, Norm, ''University of Florida Football Vault: The History of the Florida Gators'', Whitman Publishing, LLC, Atlanta, Georgia (2007).  {{ISBN|0-7948-2298-3}}.\n* Golenbock, Peter, ''Go Gators!  An Oral History of Florida's Pursuit of Gridiron Glory'', Legends Publishing, LLC, St. Petersburg, Florida (2002).  {{ISBN|0-9650782-1-3}}.\n* Hairston, Jack, ''Tales from the Gator Swamp: A Collection of the Greatest Gator Stories Ever Told'', Sports Publishing, LLC, Champaign, Illinois (2002).  {{ISBN|1-58261-514-4}}.\n* McCarthy, Kevin M., ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=_Tk-IQepI6cC  Fightin' Gators: A History of University of Florida Football]'', Arcadia Publishing, Mount Pleasant, South Carolina (2000).  {{ISBN|978-0-7385-0559-6}}.\n* Nash, Noel, ed., ''The Gainesville Sun Presents The Greatest Moments in Florida Gators Football'', Sports Publishing, Inc., Champaign, Illinois (1998).  {{ISBN|1-57167-196-X}}\n\n{{Redskins1991DraftPicks|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spencer, Jimmy}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football cornerbacks]]\n[[Category:Cincinnati Bengals players]]\n[[Category:Denver Broncos players]]\n[[Category:Florida Gators football players]]\n[[Category:New Orleans Saints players]]\n[[Category:People from Belle Glade, Florida]]\n[[Category:People from Manning, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Florida]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from South Carolina]]\n[[Category:San Diego Chargers players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|name        = Jimmy Spencer\n|image       = <!-- Only free-content images are allowed for depicting living people -- see [[WP:NONFREE]]. -->\n|image_size  =\n|alt         =\n|caption     =\n|number      = 37, 22, 33\n|position    = [[Cornerback]]\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1969|3|29|mf=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Manning, South Carolina]]\n|death_date  =\n|death_place =\n|height_ft    = 5\n|height_in    = 9\n|weight_lbs   = 188\n|high_school  = [[Glades Central High School|Glades Central]]<br>([[Belle Glade, Florida]])\n|college     = [[Florida Gators football|Florida]]\n|draftyear   = 1991\n|draftround  = 8\n|draftpick   = 215\n|pastteams   = \n* [[Washington Redskins]] ({{NFL Year|1991}})*\n* [[New Orleans Saints]] ({{NFL Year|1992}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1995}})\n* [[Cincinnati Bengals]] ({{NFL Year|1996}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1997}})\n* [[San Diego Chargers]] ({{NFL Year|1998}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1999}})\n* [[Denver Broncos]] ({{NFL Year|2000}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2003}})\n|pastteamsnote = yes\n|highlights  = \n|statleague  = NFL\n|statlabel1  = Games played\n|statvalue1  = 177\n|statlabel2  = Games started\n|statvalue2  = 81\n|statlabel3  = [[Tackle (football move)|Tackles]]\n|statvalue3  = 418\n|statlabel4  = [[Interception]]s\n|statvalue4  = 26\n|statlabel5  = [[Fumble]]s recovered\n|statvalue5  = 8\n|nfl         = SPE526203\n|pfr         = SpenJi21\n}}\n\n'''James Arthur Spencer, Jr.''' (born March 29, 1969) is an American former college and professional [[American football|football]] player who was a [[cornerback]] in the [[National Football League]] (NFL) for twelve seasons during the 1990s and early 2000s.  Spencer played [[college football]] for the [[University of Florida]], and thereafter, he played professionally for the [[New Orleans Saints]], [[Cincinnati Bengals]], [[San Diego Chargers]] and [[Denver Broncos]] of the NFL.\n\n== Early years ==\n\nSpencer was born in [[Manning, South Carolina]].<ref name=pfrprofile>Pro-Football-Reference.com, Players, [https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/S/SpenJi21.htm  Jimmy Spencer].  Retrieved October 11, 2010.</ref>  He attended [[Glades Central High School]] in [[Belle Glade, Florida]],<ref name=dbfprofile>databaseFootball.com, Players, [http://www.databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=SPENCJIM02  Jimmy Spencer] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100214053827/http://databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=SPENCJIM02 |date=February 14, 2010 }}.  Retrieved October 11, 2010.</ref> and he played high school football for the Glades Central Raiders.\n\n== College career ==\n\nSpencer accepted an athletic scholarship to attend the [[University of Florida]] in Gainesville, Florida, where he played for coach [[Galen Hall]] and coach [[Steve Spurrier]]'s [[Florida Gators football]] teams from [[1988 Florida Gators football team|1988]] to [[1990 Florida Gators football team|1990]].<ref name=ufmediaguide>''[http://web.gatorzone.com/football/media/2011/media_guide.pdf  2011 Florida Gators Football Media Guide] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402035222/http://web.gatorzone.com/football/media/2011/media_guide.pdf |date=April 2, 2012 }}'', University Athletic Association, Gainesville, Florida, pp. 105, 110, 115, 185 (2011).  Retrieved August 31, 2011.</ref>  In 1990, he blocked a punt late in the fourth quarter, which [[Richard Fain]] recovered and returned twenty-five yards for a touchdown and providing the margin of victory in the Gators' 17\u201313 victory over the [[1992 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama Crimson Tide]] in Tuscaloosa, Alabama.<ref>Norm Carlson, ''University of Florida Football Vault: The History of the Florida Gators'', Whitman Publishing, LLC, Atlanta, Georgia, p. 107 (2007).</ref>  Spencer decided to forgo his final year of NCAA eligibility after his junior season in 1990, and made himself eligible for the [[NFL Draft]].\n\n== Professional career ==\n\nThe [[Washington Redskins]] selected Spencer in the eighth round (215th pick overall) of the [[1991 NFL Draft]].<ref>Pro Football Hall of Fame, Draft History, [http://www.profootballhof.com/history/story.aspx?story_id=2027  1991 National Football League Draft].  Retrieved October 11, 2010.</ref>  Spencer played for the New Orleans Saints from {{NFL Year|1992}} to {{NFL Year|1995}}, the Cincinnati Bengals in {{NFL Year|1996}} and {{NFL Year|1997}}, the San Diego Chargers in {{NFL Year|1998}} and {{NFL Year|1999}}, and the Denver Broncos from {{NFL Year|2000}} to {{NFL Year|2003}}.<ref name=nflprofile>National Football League, Historical Players, [http://www.nfl.com/players/jimmyspencer/profile?id=SPE526203  Jimmy Spencer].  Retrieved October 11, 2010.</ref>  Statistically, his best seasons were {{NFL Year|1994}}, 1995 and 1996, when he was a regular starter for New Orleans and then Cincinnati.<ref name=pfrprofile/>\n\nIn his twelve NFL seasons, Spencer played in 177 regular season games, and started eighty-one of them.<ref name=pfrprofile/>  He finished his NFL career with twenty-six [[interception]]s, two touchdown returns, eight fumble recoveries and one fumble recovery for a touchdown.<ref name=pfrprofile/>\n\nIn 2003, Spencer worked as an assistant defensive back coach with the Broncos in addition to playing, making him the first simultaneous player/coach in the NFL since Dan Reeves in 1972.\n\n== See also ==\n\n{{Portal|American football|Biography|College football}}\n* [[Florida Gators football, 1980\u201389]]\n* [[Florida Gators football, 1990\u201399]]\n* [[History of the Denver Broncos]]\n* [[List of Florida Gators football players in the NFL]]\n* [[List of New Orleans Saints players]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* Carlson, Norm, ''University of Florida Football Vault: The History of the Florida Gators'', Whitman Publishing, LLC, Atlanta, Georgia (2007).  {{ISBN|0-7948-2298-3}}.\n* Golenbock, Peter, ''Go Gators!  An Oral History of Florida's Pursuit of Gridiron Glory'', Legends Publishing, LLC, St. Petersburg, Florida (2002).  {{ISBN|0-9650782-1-3}}.\n* Hairston, Jack, ''Tales from the Gator Swamp: A Collection of the Greatest Gator Stories Ever Told'', Sports Publishing, LLC, Champaign, Illinois (2002).  {{ISBN|1-58261-514-4}}.\n* McCarthy, Kevin M., ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=_Tk-IQepI6cC  Fightin' Gators: A History of University of Florida Football]'', Arcadia Publishing, Mount Pleasant, South Carolina (2000).  {{ISBN|978-0-7385-0559-6}}.\n* Nash, Noel, ed., ''The Gainesville Sun Presents The Greatest Moments in Florida Gators Football'', Sports Publishing, Inc., Champaign, Illinois (1998).  {{ISBN|1-57167-196-X}}\n\n{{Redskins1991DraftPicks|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spencer, Jimmy}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football cornerbacks]]\n[[Category:Cincinnati Bengals players]]\n[[Category:Denver Broncos players]]\n[[Category:Florida Gators football players]]\n